WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.175 --> 00:00:03.800
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
unless you guys have

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:06.550
been living under a rock, or
maybe you just joined Google,

00:00:06.550 --> 00:00:09.250
you're probably aware
of the myriad of ways

00:00:09.250 --> 00:00:11.440
that stress is bad for you.

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:15.100
And we're all now starting to
explore the nature of our minds

00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:18.650
and how we are, as individuals,
wound up and triggered.

00:00:18.650 --> 00:00:22.630
And so today we have
Gadadhara Pandit Das,

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:26.720
and among many things, he
is a meditation teacher.

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:28.740
And his approach
combines eastern wisdom

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:32.750
with meditation practices
to help us all do just that.

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:36.400
So I had the opportunity to
read his book in the past couple

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:38.990
of weeks, and I was
not surprised to find

00:00:38.990 --> 00:00:41.810
that, like the stories
of many wise people,

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:44.340
he faced a pretty serious
existential crisis

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:48.360
in his youth, which I'm going
to let him tell you about.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:52.075
But it launched him on
a spiritual journey.

00:00:52.075 --> 00:00:55.310
It carried him to Mumbai
and eventually New York

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:57.660
where he helps
young people like me

00:00:57.660 --> 00:00:59.820
with their quarter-life crises.

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:02.260
He works with
students at Columbia

00:01:02.260 --> 00:01:06.400
and also NYU as a
lecturer, and also

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:08.200
some of us with
our midlife crises

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:09.760
that we may be going through.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:12.180
He's been featured
on PBS and NPR,

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:14.830
and he's given a
Ted talk as well.

00:01:14.830 --> 00:01:17.390
So I just picked out a quote
from his book that really

00:01:17.390 --> 00:01:20.910
resounded with me, and I hope
it might with you as well.

00:01:20.910 --> 00:01:21.410
So.

00:01:24.060 --> 00:01:26.190
"That is taking care of
the needs of the body

00:01:26.190 --> 00:01:27.660
and ignoring the
needs of the soul

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:31.480
is like watering the
leaves, fruits, and flowers

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:34.490
of the tree, but forgetting
to water the actual root."

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:36.530
I know for many of
us, our material needs

00:01:36.530 --> 00:01:38.570
are pretty well
met here at Google.

00:01:38.570 --> 00:01:40.580
We may not be facing
an existential crisis

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:43.140
on a day-to-day basis,
but we're all here

00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:45.300
because we're concerned
about that inward journey

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:47.220
and the spiritual
aspect of things.

00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:51.490
So I'm very excited to welcome--
we can call him Pandit,

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:54.490
he has informed me,
like a political pundit.

00:01:54.490 --> 00:01:56.570
So everyone, please
welcome Pandit.

00:02:01.469 --> 00:02:03.510
GADADHARA PANDIT: So I'm
really happy to be here,

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:06.860
and I want to thank the people
who have organized this.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:08.940
Gopi was the one
who invited me here,

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:10.320
and [INAUDIBLE]
put a lot of work

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.800
into getting this whole
program organized,

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:14.100
and of course, [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:16.430
So I'm just grateful
to be able to share

00:02:16.430 --> 00:02:19.810
this wonderful information
with you on managing stress.

00:02:19.810 --> 00:02:21.260
And the first
thing I like to do,

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:26.240
because I know you're all
coming from meetings or eating,

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:29.510
emails, so I like to get
everybody on the same page.

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:32.110
So I like to a short,
mind-quieting exercise

00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:34.210
to start off our session.

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:35.980
So if you're eating, I'm sorry.

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:39.070
It might disturb your
eating just a little bit,

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:43.180
but if you can sit comfortably
and close your eyes.

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:52.280
And just feel your
feet on the floor.

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:58.570
Feel the weight of your
body sinking into the chair.

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.210
Now slowly take
a deep breath in,

00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:07.822
feeling the cool air
going in through your nose

00:03:07.822 --> 00:03:08.780
and filling your lungs.

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.220
And when your lungs
are completely filled,

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:19.800
focus on the warmer
breath leaving your body

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:22.055
through your nose.

00:03:22.055 --> 00:03:27.310
And you'll notice the inhalation
is cooler than the exhalation.

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:29.270
Again, take a deep breath in.

00:03:29.270 --> 00:03:32.570
Feel the cool air going
in through your nose

00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:33.650
and filling your lungs.

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.010
When your lungs are
completely filled,

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:45.260
you can slowly exhale,
feeling the warm breath

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:46.940
leaving your body
through your nose.

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.820
We can do this one more time.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:58.610
You can take a slow,
deep breath in,

00:03:58.610 --> 00:04:00.840
feeling the cool air
entering your nose.

00:04:04.896 --> 00:04:06.145
Filling your lungs completely.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:13.090
And then exhaling,
emptying out your lungs.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:20.165
Now you can bring your
awareness to your eyes.

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:25.880
And you can slowly
open your eyes.

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:33.400
When I feel like we get into a
room with so many people having

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.680
so many different
thoughts, it's,

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:37.410
you know, about 50,
60 people in here.

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.490
It's almost like having
50 or 60 radios playing

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:41.220
at different radio stations.

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:44.940
So now even for a minute or two,
we could all do the same thing.

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:46.300
It's quite powerful.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:47.427
Such a busy environment.

00:04:47.427 --> 00:04:49.510
Somebody described this
environment recently to me

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:50.711
like Disneyland out here.

00:04:50.711 --> 00:04:51.460
And it really was.

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:51.880
Like oh, my gosh.

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:53.750
There's food trucks,
and there's people,

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:56.600
and there's G-Bikes, and all
kinds of things going on.

00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:59.020
So it's nice to be
able to do-- everybody

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:00.990
can do the same thing
for just a little while.

00:05:00.990 --> 00:05:02.300
Now as we're talking
about stress,

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:04.133
and I know there's many
factors in our lives

00:05:04.133 --> 00:05:05.734
that causes stress,
and we're all

00:05:05.734 --> 00:05:07.400
going through a lot
of different things.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:09.921
So I like to start
off with a question.

00:05:09.921 --> 00:05:11.420
Kind of a personal
question, and you

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:14.050
can feel free to
yell out an answer.

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:15.420
Feel comfortable.

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:17.630
And the question
is, what in life

00:05:17.630 --> 00:05:21.120
right now is causing you stress?

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:24.560
I'll just tell you this
that last time I asked this,

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:26.210
it was at Bank of America.

00:05:26.210 --> 00:05:28.420
One lady, without any
hesitation, yelled out,

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:29.600
"It's my husband."

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:34.370
So if you feel that confident
and comfortable with everyone

00:05:34.370 --> 00:05:37.920
around, and you want to go ahead
and say something personal,

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:38.490
please do so.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:39.800
So what's on your mind?

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:42.850
What's causing you stress
today, or in general causes

00:05:42.850 --> 00:05:44.335
you stress?

00:05:44.335 --> 00:05:45.085
AUDIENCE: Clutter.

00:05:45.085 --> 00:05:45.410
GADADHARA PANDIT: Clutter.

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:46.370
OK.

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:47.190
Thank you.

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:47.690
All right.

00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:49.570
What else?

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:50.320
AUDIENCE: Parents.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:50.700
GADADHARA PANDIT: Parents.

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:51.040
OK.

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:51.970
We're getting into the family.

00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:53.290
It's getting more personal now.

00:05:53.290 --> 00:05:53.790
OK.

