AUDIENCE: Death of my aunt.

00:06:11.746 --> 00:06:13.160
GADADHARA PANDIT: The
death of your aunt.

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:15.250
Thank you for sharing
something so personal.

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:17.702
Anything else?

00:06:17.702 --> 00:06:18.540
AUDIENCE: Deadlines.

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:19.706
GADADHARA PANDIT: Deadlines.

00:06:19.706 --> 00:06:20.850
OK.

00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:23.560
Too much to do and
not enough time.

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:26.440
There's so many different
factors that cause us stress,

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:29.050
and according to the
American Institute of Stress,

00:06:29.050 --> 00:06:31.685
they divided up into
four basic categories.

00:06:31.685 --> 00:06:34.760
So the biggest reason
in our lives that

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:36.780
causes us stress
is our workload,

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:41.090
and a lot of stuff what
people said was work-related.

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:45.220
And it's 46% of all
stress that we experience

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:47.340
is connected with our work.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:49.310
That might sound like
a lot, but if you

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:53.160
think about it, about half
of your waking time, the time

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:55.840
that you're awake,
you're at work.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:06:58.447
If you're getting, let's
say six hours of sleep,

00:06:58.447 --> 00:07:00.280
hopefully you're getting
at least that much.

00:07:00.280 --> 00:07:01.120
Hopefully.

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:01.828
What do you have?

00:07:01.828 --> 00:07:03.840
18 hours remaining in your day.

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:06.340
And easily 10 of those
is either commuting

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:09.530
to and from work and at work, or
maybe even more than 10 hours.

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:10.830
Maybe it's 12 hours.

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:14.540
So 46% might even
be a low figure.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:15.980
It might even be more than that.

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:19.190
So but at least
46% of our stress

00:07:19.190 --> 00:07:22.300
is caused by our workload,
deadlines, things like that.

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:25.042
28%, people issues.

00:07:25.042 --> 00:07:26.750
Maybe you don't get
along with the person

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:28.240
you're sitting next to at work.

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:30.929
And you're spending
half your day at work.

00:07:30.929 --> 00:07:32.970
Or maybe you've got personal
issues in your life.

00:07:32.970 --> 00:07:38.600
Between workload and people
issues, that's 75% right there.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:42.060
Those two items take up 75%
of the stress we experience.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:45.750
20% is juggling your
work responsibilities

00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:51.077
and your personal life, and then
6% is a lack of job security.

00:07:51.077 --> 00:07:52.160
So that's also a huge one.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.210
And of course,
besides this, there

00:07:54.210 --> 00:07:56.090
may be other things
in our lives that

00:07:56.090 --> 00:07:58.960
cause us stress which
weren't covered here.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:01.100
I know one thing that
causes a lot of stress

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:04.720
for a lot of people is
just uncertainty in life.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:07.630
You're hoping to achieve
something by a certain time,

00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:10.130
or you're hoping this'll happen.

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:11.670
But it doesn't happen.

00:08:11.670 --> 00:08:12.930
You're really expecting it.

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.280
You're really counting on it,
but it just didn't happen.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:16.710
And that's causing stress.

00:08:16.710 --> 00:08:20.910
Or something that happens
that you wish didn't happen.

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:23.340
So unexpected,
unpredictable things.

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:26.120
And there was a lot of
unpredictable things in my life

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:28.790
that caused me a lot of
stress, and some of you

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:32.010
who have the book will have
a chance to read about it.

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:34.200
I grew up-- I was born in India.

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:37.340
My parents came over to
this country in 1980.

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:39.130
Moved to Los Angeles actually.

00:08:39.130 --> 00:08:40.880
The first thing that
my parents did-- they

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:42.659
didn't come over
with a lot of money.

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.480
They were doing swap
meets at Venice Beach.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:47.964
So they set up a little
shop on Venice Beach.

00:08:47.964 --> 00:08:49.380
You see all those
vendors, so they

00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:51.360
were one of those
vendors in 1980,

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.490
'81, just selling all
kinds of gift items.

00:08:54.490 --> 00:08:56.650
And I was seven years
old at that time,

00:08:56.650 --> 00:08:58.620
and that was my
first introduction

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:00.350
to American culture.

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:02.830
So I was just learning
to play basketball.

00:09:02.830 --> 00:09:05.190
I was skateboarding up
and down the boardwalk.

00:09:05.190 --> 00:09:06.610
I was listening to funk music.

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:09.166
That was what I was
exposed to in 1980,

00:09:09.166 --> 00:09:13.310
a seven-year-old Indian
kid in landed America.

00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:16.400
So they struggled really hard
to establish their business,

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.720
and it was incredible.

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:20.040
I don't know how they did
it, but within five years,

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:23.170
they established a multimillion
dollar jewelry business

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:24.807
that went across the country.

00:09:24.807 --> 00:09:26.640
It's incredible how
hard they-- I don't even

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:28.740
know what they did, because
I was just working-- I

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:30.126
was just playing, basically.

00:09:30.126 --> 00:09:32.000
But they worked so hard
that they established

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.810
an incredible business,
and then we-- my dad

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:44.060
bought this piece of land on
top of the Glendale Hills.

00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:45.980
We carved out the
hill, and that's

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:48.550
where we built our humble abode.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:50.210
This was my room right here.

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:51.450
It's no longer my room.

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:52.745
We don't live here anymore.

00:09:52.745 --> 00:09:55.090
I'm going to explain
to you why not

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:58.970
So as you can see, on the
side there's no other houses,

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:00.160
so we had the last spot.

00:10:00.160 --> 00:10:02.560
And in front my room
there was no houses,

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:03.992
so I could see all
of Downtown LA.

00:10:03.992 --> 00:10:05.950
That was like my morning
view every single day.

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:07.380
It was kind of a scenic spot.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:08.830
People would come up,
especially on Friday

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:10.570
nights and Saturday nights
to look at the view.

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.695
But that's what I would
wake up with every morning.

00:10:12.695 --> 00:10:16.210
A swimming pool in the
back, a Jacuzzi, waterfall,

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:18.770
six bedrooms, the whole works.

00:10:18.770 --> 00:10:20.260
But the story doesn't end there.

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:25.980
In 1993, my parents had a
jewelry manufacturing plant,

00:10:25.980 --> 00:10:27.590
electrical plant.

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:30.734
And during heavy rainfalls,
the thing caught on fire.

00:10:30.734 --> 00:10:32.150
And our entire
business collapsed.

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:34.790
It took us so long to
try to reestablish that.

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:36.910
Actually everything
collapsed and finished.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:38.940
And when that
business collapsed,

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:43.910
eventually, we lost all our
properties, including this one.

00:10:43.910 --> 00:10:45.540
We lost all our cars.

00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:48.320
It was a full-blown demolition.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:49.700
It was a complete wipeout.

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:51.242
We lost everything.

00:10:51.242 --> 00:10:55.670
And in an attempt to
get back up on our feet,

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.950
my dad follows a lead
from a friend of his

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.530
to go to East
Europe, because they

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:02.540
were coming out of communism.

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:05.910
And he thought that he could
import things from India

00:11:05.910 --> 00:11:08.410
and somehow try to-- because
once you've lived that life,

00:11:08.410 --> 00:11:10.030
you can't go back
to living simply.

00:11:10.030 --> 00:11:11.630
It's kind of hard.

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:13.779
So he went to Bulgaria.

00:11:13.779 --> 00:11:14.820
Anybody been to Bulgaria?

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:16.450
Anybody from Bulgaria here?

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:17.830
OK.

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:20.530
So he went to Bulgaria,
and just a little

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:23.010
while later, my mom I
decided that well, there's

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:25.760
no point in us living here,
because our life is just kind

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:26.937
of turned upside down.

00:11:26.937 --> 00:11:28.770
Might as well go to
Bulgaria and be together

00:11:28.770 --> 00:11:31.280
and figure out where
our life's going to go.

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:36.330
So in 1993, we packed our
bags and went off to Bulgaria.

00:11:39.155 --> 00:11:41.600
We went from that
incredible house

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:43.892
to living in one
of these buildings

00:11:43.892 --> 00:11:46.100
in a one-bedroom apartment
in one of these buildings.

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:50.100
Smaller, or the same size of
like a New York City apartment.

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:53.140
And Bulgaria, at that time, it
had just come out of communism.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:56.440
It was about 50 years
behind in technology.

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:58.280
So in order for me
to make a phone call,

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:00.196
I would have to walk to
the post office, which

00:12:00.196 --> 00:12:02.280
was about a mile away.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:05.120
Hardly anyone in the
country spoke English,

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:09.000
so even buying groceries
was a challenge.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.620
And the stuff that
was on television

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:13.660
was all basically in
Bulgarian and Russian,

00:12:13.660 --> 00:12:15.076
so I couldn't
understand anything.

00:12:15.076 --> 00:12:16.910
There was no
entertainment for me.

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:20.634
I went from living the LA
life, the 90210 lifestyle,

00:12:20.634 --> 00:12:22.550
to a place where I didn't
have anything to do.

00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:24.591
Even the movies that were
playing in the theaters

00:12:24.591 --> 00:12:26.960
were like a year old, and I
had seen everything already.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:30.280
There was absolutely nobody
to talk to, nothing to do.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.960
Incredible time of
introspection and reflection

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:36.100
really trying to
figure out what I

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:38.210
wanted to do with
the rest of my life.

00:12:38.210 --> 00:12:40.309
Was I going to live
and die in Bulgaria?

00:12:40.309 --> 00:12:41.350
What was going to happen?

00:12:41.350 --> 00:12:43.260
I went from a life
of complete certainty

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:46.980
to a life of
complete uncertainty.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:51.396
Two years after being in
Bulgaria for two years in 1995,

00:12:51.396 --> 00:12:52.770
the country was
kind of unstable.

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:55.640
It was becoming a
little unsafe for us,

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:58.489
so we decided to leave
and move back to the US,

00:12:58.489 --> 00:13:00.280
but we wanted to be
close to New York City,

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:02.325
so we moved to New Jersey.

00:13:02.325 --> 00:13:03.700
And my parents,
as they're trying

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:06.730
to establish another
business in New Jersey,

00:13:06.730 --> 00:13:12.320
I decide to try my hand
at the mortgage industry.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:14.235
You're thinking, why mortgages?

00:13:14.235 --> 00:13:15.020
I don't know.

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:17.311
I was just trying to figure
out what I was going to do.

00:13:17.311 --> 00:13:20.430
And we're trying to-- here
I was a loan officer trying

00:13:20.430 --> 00:13:23.820
to give loans to
people with bad credit

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:25.490
using the equity in their home.

00:13:25.490 --> 00:13:28.780
Wasn't sitting so well,
because these loans were

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:30.840
good for like three months,
and after that you'd

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:32.589
have to pay for those
loans, and it really

00:13:32.589 --> 00:13:33.770
wasn't helping people.

00:13:33.770 --> 00:13:36.350
So it wasn't something that
was sitting well with me

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:39.380
in my conscience, and I'm like,
OK, I can't do this anymore.

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:42.510
So at one point I said, I really
need to take a break from life.

00:13:42.510 --> 00:13:45.300
Because life had just been
the craziest roller coaster

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:46.760
imaginable.

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:51.660
And in 1999, I took a
huge step in my life.

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:55.720
Something I would do on my
own, really for the first time.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:59.120
To figure out what I wanted
to do and who I really was,

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:04.080
I went to live in a
monastery in India,

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:08.250
but the idea was to
be there for a month.

00:14:08.250 --> 00:14:11.700
So I was living--
I'm an only child.

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:15.210
I went from being an only child,
having everything to myself,

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:18.330
to living with 40 monks.

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:20.920
That mean shared bathrooms,
shared floor space,

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.590
sleeping on the floor in a
sleeping bag on a thin straw

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:27.000
mat, waiting in line to
use the bathroom at 4:00

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.920
in the morning, because they
got up real early, these guys.

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:32.640
Because our meditation
services started at 5:00.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:38.730
So a huge shift, but I
can say that being there

00:14:38.730 --> 00:14:42.080
and taking that time out
for myself was probably

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:44.830
the most satisfying experience
I've ever had in my life,

00:14:44.830 --> 00:14:47.920
even when we were millionaires.

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:51.440
It kind of felt like-- when
I could really reflect on it,

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.720
it felt like I'd been--
up until then I'd

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:58.145
been eating food that
didn't have enough salt.

00:14:58.145 --> 00:15:00.520
Food can be really tasty, but
if there's not enough salt,

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:04.081
no matter how else you spice
it, it just tastes bland.

00:15:04.081 --> 00:15:04.580
Right?

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:06.496
Salt just brings out the
flavor in everything.

00:15:06.496 --> 00:15:08.440
I kind of felt like
I'd been living

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:11.156
a life with not
enough salt in it.

00:15:11.156 --> 00:15:12.530
And it was such
a deep experience

00:15:12.530 --> 00:15:15.456
I extended my stay from
one month to six months.

00:15:15.456 --> 00:15:17.080
I ended up staying
in India six months,

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:20.350
here, and at
different monasteries.

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:23.610
And then eventually I decided
to come back to the US

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:27.240
after six months, and
that one-month retreat

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:33.162
has extended until
August of 2014, now.

00:15:33.162 --> 00:15:35.180
It's 15 years later.

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:37.930
I'm still living in a monastery.

00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:41.520
I'm not dressed in my
traditional saffron robes.

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:43.530
We wanted to take
it easy on you guys.

00:15:43.530 --> 00:15:45.620
After you guys just had
lunch, we weren't sure

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:48.320
how much that would affect you
seeing me in robes up here,

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:50.640
so we kind of wanted to
take it easy on everybody.

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:54.400
So I'm dressed-- I like to
say I'm undercover today.

00:15:57.340 --> 00:15:58.866
So one of the things
that I studied

00:15:58.866 --> 00:16:00.990
while I was in the monastery,
continue to study now

00:16:00.990 --> 00:16:02.690
is the nature of the mind.

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:05.400
Because the mind
is where all stress

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:09.610
and anxiety and anger and
frustration and fear-- they

00:16:09.610 --> 00:16:12.230
all rest in the mind.

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:13.660
So we did quite
a bit of studying

00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:16.530
about the nature of the mind
and became aware of our mind.

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.160
And my realization
was that the mind

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:23.250
is very much like a hard
drive of a computer.

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:26.380
That it stores everything.

00:16:26.380 --> 00:16:29.200
Like how many files
are on your computer?

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:30.230
Millions of files.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:32.410
And how many do you remember?

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:35.810
Hardly 1% of what's
on your computer.

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:38.010
That's our mind.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:41.460
It is taking in whatever
the senses bring in,

00:16:41.460 --> 00:16:42.810
whatever you see every day.

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:44.420
It all gets stored in the mind.

00:16:44.420 --> 00:16:45.650
Whatever you hear every day.

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:47.280
It all gets stored in the mind.

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:52.570
Smell, taste, touch, everything
gets stored within the mind.

00:16:52.570 --> 00:16:55.314
We're not aware of most of
the stuff that's going in.

00:16:55.314 --> 00:16:56.730
Sometimes all of
the sudden you'll

00:16:56.730 --> 00:16:58.840
remember something random,
because it was already

00:16:58.840 --> 00:16:59.650
in there.

00:16:59.650 --> 00:17:01.240
We're just not aware of it.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:02.820
So everything--
and you can imagine

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:09.470
how much we're being bombarded
by things of this world

00:17:09.470 --> 00:17:11.020
every single day.

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:14.490
In one day, how
much is going in?

00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:20.569
According to "Psychology
Today," an average person

00:17:20.569 --> 00:17:27.144
goes through between 25 to
50,000 thoughts per day.

00:17:27.144 --> 00:17:29.560
Because you're probably taking
in hundreds of thousands of

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:31.920
impressions every single day.

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:34.600
When you walked into this room,
you can't remember everything

00:17:34.600 --> 00:17:37.050
in this room, but your mind
kind of took a snapshot,

00:17:37.050 --> 00:17:38.270
and it's all in there.

00:17:38.270 --> 00:17:41.460
In a month, you can go
over a million thoughts,

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:44.754
and in over a year, it could
be 18 million thoughts.

00:17:44.754 --> 00:17:46.170
Penny for your
thoughts everybody.

00:17:46.170 --> 00:17:47.740
Right?

00:17:47.740 --> 00:17:51.630
So, and like I mentioned
earlier, most of these things

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:52.810
we don't remember.

00:17:52.810 --> 00:17:57.230
Every day, it's like we're
experiencing a daily overload.

00:17:57.230 --> 00:17:58.100
Really an overload.

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:00.308
So we shouldn't be surprised
if at the end of the day

00:18:00.308 --> 00:18:04.300
we feel stressed or
just like exhausted.

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:05.880
We're taking in a
lot of information.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:07.760
A lot of data is going
into our hard drive.

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:12.740
Thoughts.

00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:15.410
We're having so many different
thoughts every single day

00:18:15.410 --> 00:18:17.910
because of all the
impressions that are going in.

00:18:17.910 --> 00:18:20.840
A lot of our thoughts
are things from the past.

00:18:23.495 --> 00:18:24.870
The negative things
that happened

00:18:24.870 --> 00:18:28.630
a year or two years ago, or
some of the positive things

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.520
that happened, some memories.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:33.940
Unfortunately, too much time
we spend in the past thinking

00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:40.250
about the things that we've
lost, people that we've lost,

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:41.987
people that have hurt us.

00:18:41.987 --> 00:18:43.320
We can't let go of these things.

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:46.910
It's really hard, and we spend
too much time in the past.

00:18:46.910 --> 00:18:49.210
If we're not doing
that, the mind

00:18:49.210 --> 00:18:51.230
is spending time in the future.

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:53.160
What am I going
to eat for dinner?

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.620
Like how many have
planned dinner

00:18:54.620 --> 00:18:57.950
while you're eating lunch?

00:18:57.950 --> 00:18:59.240
I've done that too.

00:18:59.240 --> 00:19:01.697
Monks do that too sometimes.

00:19:01.697 --> 00:19:03.280
Because I have a
little stricter diet,

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:04.988
so I'm wondering where
am I going to eat,

00:19:04.988 --> 00:19:07.070
because I'm not sure if
I can get what I can eat.

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:08.860
So we're planning
the next meal, we're

00:19:08.860 --> 00:19:11.440
planning our weekend,
our vacation.

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:13.600
You know, just all
kinds of things.

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:15.180
When and how I'm
going to retire.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:17.180
So if it's not in the
past, it's in the present.

00:19:17.180 --> 00:19:19.080
If it's not in the
present, it's in the past.

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:22.470
It's like a set of windshield
wipers with no off switch.

00:19:22.470 --> 00:19:25.002
Imagine if from the
day you bought your car

00:19:25.002 --> 00:19:26.460
to the day you gave
it up you never

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:28.070
turned off your
windshield wipers.

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:29.444
You think you'd
kind of go crazy.

00:19:29.444 --> 00:19:30.920
Everybody would
think you're crazy.

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:32.919
But that's kind of what's
happening in the mind.

00:19:32.919 --> 00:19:36.040
Very little are we actually
in the present moment.

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:38.430
And most of it,
we're unaware of.

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:39.580
You drive down the street.

00:19:39.580 --> 00:19:43.100
So much going in, we
don't remember most of it.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:46.080
And even when we
dream-- it's amazing--

00:19:46.080 --> 00:19:47.260
our mind doesn't stop.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:51.890
When you go to sleep,
it's a 24/7 machinery.

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:55.760
Your hard drive is
running all the time.

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:57.240
So don't be
surprised, even if you

00:19:57.240 --> 00:19:58.948
haven't had an exhausting
day that you're

00:19:58.948 --> 00:20:00.150
tired at the end of the day.

00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:04.960
There's a whole lot going on up
there that we're not aware of.

00:20:04.960 --> 00:20:10.510
So now, the mind impacts the
body in a huge way, actually--

00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:12.740
very, very significant way.

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:15.680
What happens to the
mind affects the body.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:17.900
What happens to the
body affects the mind.

00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:21.070
That relationship is
very, very intimate.

00:20:21.070 --> 00:20:24.680
And there is such a
thing as positive stress,

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:27.470
that adrenaline boost, if
you want to accomplish goals,

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:29.230
maybe you're in danger.

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:32.030
That positive stress helps
you defend yourself, protect

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:34.010
yourself, but you don't
want to be living even

00:20:34.010 --> 00:20:37.340
on that adrenaline
boost all the time.

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:39.940
So the things that we
want to talk about today

00:20:39.940 --> 00:20:43.400
are things like stress, anger,
and anxiety that ultimately

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:47.430
take a toll on our body.

00:20:47.430 --> 00:20:49.100
Things like high blood pressure.

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:50.880
We know that's a
product of the mind.

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:52.020
Think about it.

00:20:52.020 --> 00:20:54.650
It's not necessarily the
circumstances around you.

00:20:54.650 --> 00:20:57.024
It's your mind that's giving
you high blood pressure.

00:20:57.024 --> 00:20:58.940
We're going to explain
that a little bit more.

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:00.910
Your mind is creating fatigue.

00:21:00.910 --> 00:21:02.410
It's your mind
that's preventing you

00:21:02.410 --> 00:21:03.570
from getting a
good night's sleep.

00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:05.653
Like you just can't let
it go-- the project you're

00:21:05.653 --> 00:21:07.750
working on or maybe
the conflict you had.

00:21:07.750 --> 00:21:10.280
You're holding onto it,
and you can't fall asleep.

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:12.270
You're trying, but the
mind just plays it over.

00:21:12.270 --> 00:21:13.540
It's in instant replay mode.

00:21:13.540 --> 00:21:15.630
You can't get it out.

00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:18.400
And then, of course, in a
worst case, heart attacks

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:19.030
and strokes.

00:21:19.030 --> 00:21:21.670
We can note that's all
a product of the mind.

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:26.380
So good way to understand this,
how the mind affects the body,

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:27.630
is the phenomena of nightmare.

00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:29.574
Anybody recently
have a nightmare?

00:21:29.574 --> 00:21:31.240
For some of us, maybe
it's more graphic.

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:32.490
You saw a horror
movie, and then you're

00:21:32.490 --> 00:21:33.700
like the victim
in your nightmare.

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:33.980
You know?

00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:35.896
Like, oh, my God, I'm
being chased by somebody

00:21:35.896 --> 00:21:37.040
with a hacksaw.

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:39.054
And then when you
wake up from that,

00:21:39.054 --> 00:21:40.970
what are your bodily
symptoms when you wake up

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:43.011
from a nightmare and
realize it was just a dream?

00:21:46.410 --> 00:21:47.340
AUDIENCE: Sweating.

00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:48.215
GADADHARA PANDIT: OK.

00:21:48.215 --> 00:21:48.890
You're sweating.

00:21:48.890 --> 00:21:49.410
What else?

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:50.310
AUDIENCE: Your heart's pounding.

00:21:50.310 --> 00:21:52.180
GADADHARA PANDIT:
Your heart's pounding.

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.263
You feel like the guys may
still be in the closet.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:21:59.540
Everybody responded to that.

00:21:59.540 --> 00:22:01.790
So your heart's beating.

00:22:01.790 --> 00:22:03.739
You're breathing faster, maybe.

00:22:03.739 --> 00:22:06.030
And to think about it, you
were comfortably tucked away

00:22:06.030 --> 00:22:09.810
in your bed in beautiful
Northern California.

00:22:09.810 --> 00:22:12.570
The sun is always shining,
and the hills are flowing.

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:13.430
Right?

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:16.280
But what made your
heart beat faster?

00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:17.770
It was your mind.

00:22:17.770 --> 00:22:19.430
You weren't running.

00:22:19.430 --> 00:22:21.390
What made your breathing faster?

00:22:21.390 --> 00:22:22.950
It was your mind.

00:22:22.950 --> 00:22:25.880
What made perspiration
come out of your body?

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:29.340
How hard you have to work out
for perspiration to come out?

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:31.220
Think about it for a moment.

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:34.310
How hard do you have to run
on that treadmill before like,

00:22:34.310 --> 00:22:36.900
OK, finally I'm sweating?

00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:40.250
But here, it's like
you're sitting still.

00:22:40.250 --> 00:22:44.160
You're as inactive as possible.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:48.060
And the mind says, well,
we're going to make you sweat.

00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:50.450
So it's a product of the mind.

00:22:50.450 --> 00:22:53.250
The physical health is
a product of the mind.

00:22:53.250 --> 00:22:58.450
Who knows which movie
this quote is from?

00:22:58.450 --> 00:22:59.975
"The mind makes it real."

00:22:59.975 --> 00:23:00.540
Come on.

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:01.780
Someone's got to know.

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:04.020
"The Matrix." "Inception"
is a good guess.

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:04.810
It was similar.

00:23:04.810 --> 00:23:05.710
Who said Matrix?

00:23:05.710 --> 00:23:06.210
OK.

00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:06.710
Yes.

00:23:06.710 --> 00:23:08.430
It's one of my favorite movies.

